---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
import MapLink from '../../components/MapLink.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Bermuda Beaches — The Curated Guide"
  description="The best beaches in Bermuda: Horseshoe Bay, Tobacco Bay, John Smith's Bay, Warwick Long Bay, and Elbow Beach. Real guide with access, facilities, and what to expect."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero hero--image" style="padding-block: var(--space-16); --hero-image: url('/Pilot.BM/images/beach-pink-sand.webp');">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/visit" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Visiting</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Beaches</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Bermuda's Beaches</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Pink sand, turquoise water, and some of the most photogenic shoreline in the Atlantic.
        A curated five-beach guide — no filler.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- Practical note -->
      <div class="alert alert-info" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <strong>Before you go:</strong> Bermuda enforces a <strong>reef-safe sunscreen rule</strong> at its beaches.
        Oxybenzone and octinoxate are banned. Bring a mineral sunscreen or buy one on-island.
        This is strictly enforced at the beach parks.
      </div>

      <!-- Horseshoe Bay -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: flex-start; justify-content: space-between; gap: var(--space-4); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <div>
            <span class="badge badge-tier-anchor" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Must-visit</span>
            <h2 style="margin: 0;">Horseshoe Bay Beach</h2>
            <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-1); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); flex-wrap: wrap;">
              Southampton Parish
              <MapLink query="Horseshoe Bay Beach, Bermuda" />
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="figure">
          <img src="/Pilot.BM/images/beach-horseshoe.webp" alt="Pink sand and turquoise water at Horseshoe Bay, Southampton, Bermuda" width="1600" height="900" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        </figure>
        <p>
          <strong>Horseshoe Bay</strong> is Bermuda's signature beach — the one on every postcard, every travel
          magazine cover, every Instagram post. The pink sand is real and striking. The water is an
          extraordinary shade of turquoise. The horseshoe shape of the bay creates calm, swimmable conditions
          even when the open Atlantic is choppy.
        </p>
        <p>
          The pink colour comes from crushed pink coral, shells, and the red-pink skeleton of foraminifera —
          a single-celled organism. You can see the pink grains mixed with the white sand up close.
        </p>
        <p>
          It is the <strong>busiest beach on the island</strong> and can be very crowded in peak summer.
          If crowds bother you, go early (before 9am) or visit in spring/autumn.
          Adjacent <strong>Warwick Long Bay</strong> (see below) offers a similar setting with fewer people.
        </p>
        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Getting there:</strong> Bus Route 7 from Hamilton (30–40 min, $4) stops at the beach entrance.
            The most convenient public transport option on the island.
            Scooters and minicars can park at the designated lot.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: var(--space-2) 0 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Facilities:</strong> Beach bar and café (seasonal, May–October), changing rooms, showers,
            chair and umbrella rental, lifeguard service (seasonal). The most facilitated beach on the island.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Tobacco Bay -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-featured" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Excellent snorkelling</span>
          <h2 style="margin: 0;">Tobacco Bay</h2>
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-1); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); flex-wrap: wrap;">
            St. George's Parish — near the UNESCO World Heritage town
            <MapLink query="Tobacco Bay, Bermuda" />
          </p>
        </div>
        <figure class="figure">
          <img src="/Pilot.BM/images/ocean-rocks.webp" alt="Rock formations and clear water along the Bermuda shoreline near Tobacco Bay" width="1600" height="900" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        </figure>
        <p>
          Tobacco Bay is Bermuda's best snorkelling beach — calm, sheltered water with interesting rock
          formations, sea fans, and regular fish activity. The bay is small and protected, making it
          excellent for families with children and for anyone who wants to snorkel without fighting waves.
        </p>
        <p>
          It's in St. George's Parish, making it convenient to combine with a half-day exploring the
          historic town of St. George's (a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 2000). Walk the fortifications,
          have lunch in town, then take a taxi to Tobacco Bay for the afternoon.
        </p>
        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Getting there:</strong> Taxi from St. George's town (~5 min) or scooter.
            Not directly on a major bus route — factor this into planning.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: var(--space-2) 0 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Facilities:</strong> Seasonal beach bar, snorkel rental. No lifeguard.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- John Smith's Bay -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-standard" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Locals' favourite</span>
          <h2 style="margin: 0;">John Smith's Bay</h2>
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-1); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); flex-wrap: wrap;">
            Devonshire Parish
            <MapLink query="John Smith's Bay, Bermuda" />
          </p>
        </div>
        <figure class="figure">
          <img src="/Pilot.BM/images/shoreline.webp" alt="Quiet stretch of pink-sand shoreline backed by rocky headlands, Bermuda" width="1600" height="900" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        </figure>
        <p>
          John Smith's Bay is where Bermudians go on their days off. Fewer tourists, more families.
          The long stretch of pink sand is flanked by rocky headlands, giving it a natural, unhurried atmosphere.
          No beach bar, no chair rental — just the beach.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is the beach to choose if you want the Bermuda experience without the Horseshoe Bay crowd.
          Bring your own water, snacks, and sunscreen. The absence of facilities is part of the appeal.
        </p>
        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Getting there:</strong> Bus Route 1 (Hamilton to St. George's). Scooter/minicar also practical.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: var(--space-2) 0 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Facilities:</strong> None. No lifeguard. Bring everything you need.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Warwick Long Bay -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-standard" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Best long walk</span>
          <h2 style="margin: 0;">Warwick Long Bay</h2>
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-1); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); flex-wrap: wrap;">
            Warwick Parish — adjacent to Horseshoe Bay
            <MapLink query="Warwick Long Bay, Bermuda" />
          </p>
        </div>
        <figure class="figure">
          <img src="/Pilot.BM/images/beach-cove.webp" alt="Sweeping south-shore beach and cove at Warwick, Bermuda" width="1600" height="900" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        </figure>
        <p>
          Warwick Long Bay is Horseshoe Bay's quieter neighbour — separated by a rocky point, accessible
          on foot via the beach path. It's a long, sweeping stretch of south shore beach without the
          facilities or crowds of Horseshoe. An excellent alternative if Horseshoe is packed.
        </p>
        <p>
          The south shore walk between Horseshoe Bay and Warwick Long Bay (and on to Jobson's Cove and
          Chaplin Bay) is one of the best short hikes in Bermuda — pink sand, dramatic rock formations,
          and Atlantic views the whole way.
        </p>
        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Getting there:</strong> Same as Horseshoe Bay — Bus Route 7. Walk along the south shore path.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: var(--space-2) 0 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Facilities:</strong> None. No lifeguard.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Elbow Beach -->
      <article style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
        <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          <span class="badge badge-tier-standard" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Calm water</span>
          <h2 style="margin: 0;">Elbow Beach</h2>
          <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-top: var(--space-1); display: flex; align-items: center; gap: var(--space-3); flex-wrap: wrap;">
            Paget Parish — fronts the Elbow Beach Hotel
            <MapLink query="Elbow Beach, Bermuda" />
          </p>
        </div>
        <figure class="figure">
          <img src="/Pilot.BM/images/coast-cliffs.webp" alt="Calm south-shore water and coastline near Elbow Beach, Paget, Bermuda" width="1600" height="900" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
        </figure>
        <p>
          Elbow Beach is a hotel beach (fronting the Elbow Beach Bermuda resort) but remains open to the
          public. The water is notably calmer than Horseshoe Bay, making it a good choice for families
          with young children or anyone who prefers gentle swimming.
        </p>
        <p>
          The walk from Paget to Elbow Beach is pleasant, and the beach itself is less crowded than
          Horseshoe Bay. The hotel serves drinks and food to hotel guests and, at times, to the public —
          check in advance.
        </p>
        <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-5); margin-top: var(--space-4);">
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Getting there:</strong> Taxi from Hamilton (~10–15 min) or scooter. Not on a direct bus route to the hotel entrance.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: var(--space-2) 0 0; color: var(--color-ink);">
            <strong>Facilities:</strong> Hotel facilities nearby; lifeguard service varies.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Practical info -->
      <section style="background-color: var(--color-sand); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-top: var(--space-8);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Practical beach information</h2>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">What to bring</h3>
        <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
          <li><strong>Reef-safe mineral sunscreen</strong> (required — oxybenzone/octinoxate banned)</li>
          <li>Water (the beach bars charge resort prices for water)</li>
          <li>Snorkel gear (rentable at Tobacco Bay and Horseshoe; bring your own for other beaches)</li>
          <li>Exact change if taking the bus ($4 per ride; passes from Ferry Terminal)</li>
          <li>Cash for the beach bar at Horseshoe Bay (cards sometimes unreliable)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">Water temperature by month</h3>
        <div class="table-wrapper">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Season</th>
                <th>Months</th>
                <th>Water temp</th>
                <th>Swimming</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Spring</td>
                <td>March–May</td>
                <td>18–22°C (64–72°F)</td>
                <td>Cool, suit helps</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Summer</td>
                <td>June–September</td>
                <td>26–29°C (79–84°F)</td>
                <td>Excellent</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Autumn</td>
                <td>October–November</td>
                <td>23–26°C (73–79°F)</td>
                <td>Very good</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Winter</td>
                <td>December–February</td>
                <td>17–19°C (63–66°F)</td>
                <td>Cold; dedicated swimmers only</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-3); margin-top: var(--space-6);">
          Portuguese man-o-war season
        </h3>
        <div class="alert alert-warning">
          <strong>October–May:</strong> Portuguese man-o-war (Physalia physalis) appear on Bermuda's south
          shore beaches during autumn, winter, and spring. Their tentacles can cause significant pain even
          after the creature is dead. Always check current conditions with your hotel or lifeguard before
          swimming during these months. Lifeguards will flag beaches when man-o-war are present.
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
